qas.question: What is the dominant type of house in Philadelphia?
What are row houses called outside of Philadelphia?
Name a type of row house in the city?

answers.text: Victorian-style homes in North Philadelphia to twin row houses in West Philadelphia

qas.question: How old is most of the housing in Philadelphia?
Which neighborhood has the oldest housing in America?

context: For much of Philadelphia's history, the typical home has been the <a0_0>row house<a0_0/>. The row house was introduced to the United States via Philadelphia in the early 19th century and, for a time, row houses built elsewhere in the United States were known as "<a1_0>Philadelphia rows<a1_0/>". A variety of row houses are found throughout the city, from <a2_0>Victorian-style homes in North Philadelphia to twin row houses in West Philadelphia<a2_0/>. While newer homes are scattered throughout the city, much of the housing is from the <a3_0>early 20th century or older<a3_0/>. The great age of the homes has created numerous problems, including blight and vacant lots in many parts of the city, while other neighborhoods such as <a4_0>Society Hill<a4_0/>, which has the largest concentration of 18th-century architecture in the United States, have been rehabilitated and gentrified.
